hemical warfare materials, and once the OPCW confirmed the declaration, to destroy them.</p><p>The former Libyan government declared possession of 25 metric tonnes of bulk mustard agent and 1,400 metric tonnes of precursor chemicals, which are used to make chemical weapons. It also declared more than 3,500 unfilled aerial bombs designed for use with chemical warfare agents such as sulphur mustard, and three chemical weapons production facilities.</p><p>The Foreign Office said it was waiting to see the scale to which Gaddafi misled the international community, but one source said the find was big.</p><p>At the weekend Blair, speaking on BBC's Andrew Marr Show, defended the British rapprochement with Gaddafi on the basis that he had abandoned his weapons of mass destruction.</p>","headline":"Britain sends officials to Libya to help destroy chemical weapons","trailText":"<p>Size of stockpile found by NTC suggests Tony Blair was misled by Colonel Gaddifi's promise to destroy weapons in 2004</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"2","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/11/14/1321308195045/Colonel-Gaddafi--003.jpg","wordcount":"363","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"381838086","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"5459313","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Patrick Wintour","newspaperEditionDate":"2011-11-15T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1662363","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2011-11-17T22:03:41Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/nov/14/british-officials-help-libya-chemical-weapons","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/world/2011/nov/14/british-officials-help-libya-chemical-weapons","tags":[{"id":"world/libya","webTitle":"Libya","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/libya","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardian